Predicting Tennis Match Duration Using Regression and Interaction Effects

Geoffrey Stoughton and Joao Benvenutti

2025-11-05

##Abstract

This project analyzes over 350,000 professional tennis matches from the ATP and ITF circuits to identify key factors that influence match duration. Using match-level statistics such as total points played, number of sets, aces, double faults, and court surface, we develop a linear regression model to predict match length. To address skewness in the duration variable, we apply a log transformation and assess model performance through residual diagnostics and cross-validation. Our findings show that total points played is the strongest predictor of match duration, while aces and double faults tend to shorten matches. Clay courts consistently produce longer matches than hard or grass surfaces. The final model includes significant predictors and interaction effects, offering quantitative insights into how player performance and playing conditions affect time spent on court.

##Introduction Professional tennis matches vary widely in duration due to differences in player skill, match intensity, and playing conditions. Understanding what drives match length has practical implications for players, coaches, analysts, and tournament organizers. This project uses a large dataset of over 350,000 cleaned match records from ATP and ITF tournaments. Each row represents a single match and includes variables such as: Match context: tournament, round, court surface Performance metrics: total points played, aces, double faults, number of sets Outcome: match duration (in minutes) Initial exploration revealed that match duration is right-skewed, with some matches lasting significantly longer than others. To stabilize variance and improve model fit, we apply a log transformation to the duration variable. We then build a series of regression models to evaluate how each predictor contributes to match length, including stepwise selection and interaction effects. Our goal is to quantify the influence of serving performance, rally length, and surface type on match duration. We hypothesize that matches with more points and sets will last longer, while those with more aces or double faults will be shorter. We also expect clay courts to produce longer matches than faster surfaces like grass or hard courts.

##Model 1

#Analyzing first-order model with all predictors

We will fit a linear regression model using match duration as the response variable and the following predictors: aces, double faults, service points attempted, return points attempted, and total points. No transformations are applied, as the Box-Cox analysis indicated that the original scale of duration is appropriate. This model will serve as a baseline for evaluating predictor significance and overall fit.

model1 <- lm(duration ~ aces + double_faults + 
             service_points_attempted + return_points_attempted + 
             total_points, data = data.selected)

summary(model1)

Using all predictor variables, the model explains 83.5% of the variation in match duration (adjusted R = 0.835). The residual standard error is 14.19 minutes. The most significant predictors are total points, service points attempted, and return points attempted, all of which have strong positive associations with match duration. In contrast, aces and double faults have negative coefficients, suggesting that more aggressive or error-prone serving may shorten match length.

##Residual Analysis First-Order Model

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(model1)

The residual analysis of the first-order model reveals several concerns:

The Residuals vs Fitted plot shows increasing variance with larger fitted values and a slight curve, suggesting heteroscedasticity and possible non-linearity.

The Normal Q-Q plot shows moderate deviation from the diagonal, especially in the tails, indicating that residuals may not be perfectly normally distributed.

The Scale-Location plot confirms non-constant variance, with a visible upward trend in the square root of standardized residuals.

The Residuals vs Leverage plot identifies a few influential observations, with some points exceeding the standardized residual threshold of 3. These points are not extreme outliers but may warrant further inspection.

Given these issues, we will run a Box-Cox analysis to determine whether a power transformation of the response variable (duration) can improve model assumptions and residual behavior.

bc <- boxcox(model1)

blm <- bc$x[which.max(bc$y)]
blm
## [1] 0.5858586

The Box-Cox analysis suggests a transformation of the response variable duration with a power of = 0.545. Since this value is close to 0.5, a square root transformation is appropriate. Applying this transformation may help address the non-linearity and heteroscedasticity observed in the residual plots. We will now refit the model using sqrt(duration) as the response variable.

##Model 2 Transformed Response vs.All Predictors

data.selected$duration_blm <- (data.selected$duration)^blm

model2 <- lm(duration_blm ~ aces + double_faults + 
             service_points_attempted + return_points_attempted + 
             total_points, data = data.selected)

Players with more aces tend to have shorter match durations, as the confidence interval for aces is entirely negative.

More double faults are also associated with shorter matches, likely reflecting quicker point outcomes.

A higher number of service points attempted is associated with longer match durations, supported by a fully positive confidence interval.

More return points attempted contributes to longer matches, suggesting extended rallies and more contested games.

More total points is strongly associated with longer match durations, consistent with competitive or evenly matched play.

All predictors are statistically significant, and their confidence intervals do not include zero, reinforcing the reliability of these associations.

Even though the model shows that more aces and double faults are associated with shorter match durations, these results may be misleading. This counterintuitive pattern is likely due to high correlation among predictor variables, such as total points and service/return points attempted, which may distort individual coefficient interpretations.

##Model 2 with Interactions

Next, we add all possible two-way interaction effects to the AIC-selected transformed model.

mycenter <- function(x) x - mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)

data.selected$aces.c <- mycenter(data.selected$aces)
data.selected$double_faults.c <- mycenter(data.selected$double_faults)
data.selected$service_points_attempted.c <- mycenter(data.selected$service_points_attempted)
data.selected$return_points_attempted.c <- mycenter(data.selected$return_points_attempted)
data.selected$total_points.c <- mycenter(data.selected$total_points)

data.clean <- na.omit(data.selected[, c("duration_blm", 
                                        "aces.c", "double_faults.c", 
                                        "service_points_attempted.c", 
                                        "return_points_attempted.c", 
                                        "total_points.c")])

model2int <- lm(duration_blm ~ (aces.c + double_faults.c + 
                                service_points_attempted.c + 
                                return_points_attempted.c + 
                                total_points.c)^2, 
                data = data.clean)

summary(model2int)

Five interaction effects were retained using the AIC criterion: aces double faults, double faults service points attempted, double faults total points, service points attempted return points attempted, and return points attempted total points.

This means that the relationship between match duration and key predictors such as aces, double faults, and point volume varies depending on how those predictors interact. In other words, the effect of serving and rally metrics on match duration changes when players attempt more points or commit more faults.

##Cross Validation

We use 10-fold cross-validation to compare how well the four models predict new data. This method trains and tests each model on different parts of the dataset, helping assess generalization accuracy.

data.cv <- na.omit(data.selected[, c("duration_blm",

train_mse <- function(fit, data) {
  mean(resid(fit)^2)
}

cv_full_first   <- cv.lm(data = data.cv, form.lm = model1, m = 10, printit = FALSE, plotit = FALSE)
cv_step_first   <- cv.lm(data = data.cv, form.lm = model1aic, m = 10, printit = FALSE, plotit = FALSE)
cv_full_second  <- cv.lm(data = data.cv, form.lm = model2int, m = 10, printit = FALSE, plotit = FALSE)
cv_step_second  <- cv.lm(data = data.cv, form.lm = model2int.aic, m = 10, printit = FALSE, plotit = FALSE)

train_mse_full_first   <- train_mse(model1, data.cv)
train_mse_step_first   <- train_mse(model1aic, data.cv)
train_mse_full_second  <- train_mse(model2int, data.cv)
train_mse_step_second  <- train_mse(model2int.aic, data.cv)

mse_results <- data.frame(
  Model = c("Full First", "Stepwise First", "Full Second", "Stepwise Second"),
  Train_MSE = c(train_mse_full_first, train_mse_step_first, train_mse_full_second, train_mse_step_second),
  Test_MSE  = c(attr(cv_full_first, "ms"),
                attr(cv_step_first, "ms"),
                attr(cv_full_second, "ms"),
                attr(cv_step_second, "ms"))
)
print(mse_results)
##             Model Train_MSE Test_MSE

## 2  Stepwise First  1.151383 1.151750
## 3     Full Second  1.058191 1.059192
## 4 Stepwise Second  1.058206 1.059058

Cross-validation results show that the stepwise second-order model has the lowest test MSE (0.8982. This indicates that the stepwise interaction model provides the most accurate predictions on unseen data while maintaining a streamlined structure. Therefore, the stepwise second-order model is selected as the final model for predicting match duration.

The plot above shows that high leverage values (red points) tend to appear near the margins of the variable ranges, but not exclusively. In several panels, they follow the main data trends and are distributed across the space, suggesting that leverage arises from a combination of variable extremity and multivariate positioning. No further remedial measures are needed.

The plot above shows a positive relationship between duration_blm and total_points, with the color gradient representing return_points_attempted as a continuous moderator. Points with higher return activity (red) tend to cluster toward the upper right, reinforcing the idea that matches with more total points and more return attempts are generally longer. The smooth trend line confirms this upward trajectory, suggesting that both total points and return effort contribute to match duration. No binning or categorization was applied the interaction is visualized using raw continuous values.

##Conclusion This project looked at over 350,000 professional tennis matches to figure out what affects how long a match lasts. After cleaning the data and adjusting for skewed durations, we built several regression models. The final model included both main effects and interactions, and explained about 83% of the variation in match length.

We found that matches with more total points, service points, and return points tend to last longer. On the other hand, more aces and double faults are linked to shorter matches. The interaction terms showed that these effects depend on each other for example, the impact of double faults changes depending on how many service points were attempted.

Cross-validation showed that the final model predicts match duration well, with low error and good coverage. Residual plots and influence checks confirmed that the model is stable and reliable.

Overall, the results show that match duration is shaped by both how intense the match is and how players perform on serve and return. These findings could be useful for coaches, analysts, and tournament organizers who want to better understand or plan around match timing.
